All_symptoms: Blood glucose increased Fatigue Insulin resistance Limb discomfort
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Thurs, Nov 4 2:45pm first vaccine dose. Only minor arm discomfort for Thursday and Friday. Some fatigue on Saturday and Sunday. By Monday afternoon, November 8 she started having unexplained high blood sugar reading (via cgm). This continues for three full days so far and caused her to miss one day of online school. It is if there is massive insulin resistance -- that we giver her insulin to cover meals but the insulin does not act how it normally does (we switched pods and insulin bottles to ensure it was not an equipment issue). She is 10 and has some puberty hormonal bg swings but we have not seen anything like this. The insulin, though supposed to start to take effect in 15 minutes is taking many hours. By then we have over corrected and then she crashes low. In comparison to previous weeks, she is far above her average time in range, average bg number and standard deviation with 176bg, 51% in range , 10% very high and 60 SD.  The week before in comparison was 150bg, 65% in rance, 1% very high and 42SD. These numbers do not show the immense fear and exhaustion that this has caused. We just want people to be aware that for Type 1 kids there may be a delayed amount of bg highs and lows due to increased insulin resistance. As T1D parents we always expect bg swings with any medicine or vaccine but this has been very different and social media searches indicate this is happening to others though overlooked and underreported as this is considered a 'normal' response. But the severity needs to be noted. My kiddo should never be 400+ after eating anything if she has insulin on board. It is very scary and just want someone to know. We hope this wears off soon. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Medication administration error.  Patient was supposed to receive pediatric dose of Pfizer vaccine 0.2 mL . Instead, patient received 0.25 mL booster dose of Moderna on 11/12/2021 at 10:30 am. I immediately noted error as soon as I finished administering the vaccine and spoke with patient's parent immediately about the incident. I recommended that the patient wait 30 minutes for observation.  I then immediately called to report occurrence to a health agency. We were advised to let parents know about the error, have them wait 30 minutes,  and advise them that we would be in contact for information and guidance regarding the second dose of the vaccine once we receive instruction from the CDC's standpoint.  Patient was under our observation for 30 minutes post-vaccine administration and had no signs or symptoms of adverse reaction. Gave  health agency contact information and phone number to patient's parents to call with any additional questions or concerns and verbalized that we would be in touch to give further guidance on the plan for the second dose.

All_symptoms: Abdominal pain Crying Emotional distress Erythema Face injury
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client was vaccinated with pediatric Pfizer at 9:40am. Client denied symptoms other than mild pain at the injection site. At 9:45am, client lost consciousness and fell from a standing position and hit her left cheek and above her eyebrow. Multiple RNs in the clinic responded. The RN and the client's mom rolled the client onto her back and she regained consciousness immediately. Client was tearful and upset. Client reported that her cheek and head hurt. Ice was applied to the cheek (there was redness and swelling, but no bleeding) and juice was provided. Client was oriented and answered questions appropriately. Pupils were equal. Client denied nausea. Clients's mother stated that the client has no history of fainting. At 9:55am, client was moved into a sitting position, which was well tolerated. At 10:00am, client was moved into a chair, which was also well tolerated. Client reported feeling better and drank more juice and had crackers. Client reported that her 'belly hurt' briefly around 10:03am, but this last less than one minute. Before leaving clinic, client reported that she was feeling better, has soreness on her cheek and denied nausea. Client left the clinic at 10:22am.  Client's mother declined EMS services and was provided with education to call their pediatrician if she noticed signs of a concussion (nausea, headache, confusion) or worsening of the pain on the child's cheek. Client's mother verbalized understanding and planned to bring the client home to rest.

The patient denied any pain. The head of the bed was elevated. The patient denied any trouble breathing. At 5:24pm the patient's BP was 90/62 and HR was 110. At 5:24pm the patient vomited. At 5:24pm EMS was called. At 5:29pm the patient reported that he no longer felt dizzy. The patient was asked if he was itchy anywhere and he reported that his back was itchy. The back was assessed and hives were present across his back. The patient's parents reported that the patient has a history of breaking out in hives. The patient reported that his back was itchy before receiving the vaccine. At 5:31pm BP was 102/72 and RR 13. The fire department arrived at 5:35pm and assumed care of the patient. At 5:40pm  BP was 118/77, HR 74, and O2 Sat 95%. At 5:41pm paramedics arrived on site and assumed care of the patient. At 5:43pm the patient was transported by the paramedics to the emergency room.

All_symptoms: Asthenia Auscultation Dizziness Dyspnoea Heart rate increased
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient observed post COVID-19 immunization for just a few minutes before she had dizziness and nausea. She proceeded to pass out and urinate while being attended to by the nursing staff. This was very brief as she began responding to supine positioning. Pulse was 55 and regular by auscultation. She needed to vomit (which she never did). Her legs were raised. She responded within a minute saying she felt better. Vitals at this point (1:59 pm) P-89, BP 98/60, pO2 100%. She was moved by wheelchair to a lobby couch where she chose to remain sitting and drink water. She felt almost back to normal. She conversed easily. After 25 min observation, Mom (present the whole time) was sent to get car and patient was taken to the vehicle. She appeared well at discharge. Patient's mom was aware of post admin emergencies having had 2 other children vaccinated: Difficulty breathing, swelling of face and throat, a fast heartbeat, a bad rash all over body, dizziness and weakness. Vasovagal reaction to injection, now resolved. Plan: Allow next observation for dose 2 to be in supine position after admin. Pfizer lot #FK5127 R deltoid.
LAB_DATA: Exam- PERRLA w/conjugate EOMs. Facies symmetrical. Ht regular. Lungs clear. EXTR clear. CN 2-12 intact. Gait normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 5 year old previously healthy boy who presented to the emergency department with an episode of altered mental status/pre-syncope like event that self resolved or did so with IVF.  This occurred 3 days after his 1st Pfizer Covid vaccination.  He presented to the ED with mild hypothermia to 95F, mild hypoglycemia to 63, and a K+ of 2.7.  He had negative EKG, echo, and troponin in the ed.  He had no fevers.  His drug screen was negative.  His lab abnormalities resolved on recheck.  he was observed for 7 hours in the ED and sent home as he was well appearing.   He did have a mildly sore arm reported on the day of the vaccination and complained of mild belly pain twice the following day, but otherwise had no clear or obvious vaccine reactions.   This episode reported was not clearly vaccine related but is being reported as it's etiology was certain.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the 1st COVID-19 vaccination today in the office.  Per parent report the patient briefly lost consciousness. When I arrived to the exam room he was lying on his back and his mother was holding his legs above his head. By that time he was appropriately responsive and alert and oriented. No signs of respiratory distress, no edema, or other signs of anaphylaxis. He was given a drink of water. He was observed for 20 minutes in the exam room and remained at his neurologic baseline. I suspect syncopal reaction after the vaccination. This is not a contraindication to the second vaccine for COVID as I do not believe this was an anaphylactic reaction. Mom verbalized understanding.
HISTORY: juvenile idiopathic scoliosis of lumbar region innocent heart murmur

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the first dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine and about a minute later, he threw up, as he walked away. His mother stated that he has a history of passing out after blood draws and shots. He was lain on a cot and offered some juice to sip slowly. He was chatting throughout and stated ""I'm fine- I don't know why I threw up."" After 30 minutes of observation had passed, his mother said that he was fine and they were ready to leave. BP was 108/70, pulse was 88bpm and respiration was 18 per minute.

All_symptoms: Dizziness Eye movement disorder Fall Feeling cold Loss of consciousness
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received his Pfizer vaccine and 30 seconds after that, he felt faint and fell to the floor per client's mother. Mother stated he did not hit his head when he fell. Client regained consciousness a few seconds later and insisted on getting up and stated "" I am fine."" Client was assessed for pain, bleeding, bruising, client  stated ""I am fine.""  Client was transferred to the cot and assisted in lying position with feet elevate. Client stated "" I feel better"" and asked if he can sit up, client was given water, juice and crackers. After eating, client was transferred to a chair, client's mother went to check on him and put a mask on him. Client's eyes rolled back and started falling, client was lowered to the ground and regained consciousness a few seconds after. He complained of feeling cold and stated that his heart was racing. The EMT was called and arrived in less than 5 minutes. BP was 128/78 Heart rate was 90. Client was cleared by the EMT personnel to go home and client stated that he felt ""fine.""

All_symptoms: Confusional state Dizziness Fall Fatigue Head injury
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient's father reported patient received first dose pediatric COVID Pfizer vaccine during drive thru vaccine clinic. Family was waiting  in the car during the required 15 minute monitoring time when patient became stiff and started to fall back, hitting head on back window of truck. Incident was witnessed by patient's father and patient's sister. Father honked horn to alert staff who responded to patient who was responsive and able to answer questions. Patient reported feeling dizzy and tired and was unsure what happened. Patient appeared confused about situation but remembered getting vaccine and was oriented to time and place. Patient's blood pressure was 98/60 and patient was provided a bottle of water to drink. Father reported patient struck back of head on back window of truck but it did not seem to be a hard strike. Patient reported no pain or discomfort to her head. Patient leaned back on seat, drank water, and had second blood pressure reading of 100/65 5 minutes after first check. Patient reported feeling very tired and wanted to rest while being monitored. Patient sat in front seat of truck with father and finished out a 30 minute monitoring at 16:48. Nurse explained to father possible cause of syncopal episode and to monitor child for the rest of the evening. Nurse also explained when seeking care at urgent care, emergency room, or healthcare provider may be appropriate if patient does not continue to improve.

Nurse 1 was pulling out needle from vial after dilution for pediatric Pfizer COVID 19 Vaccine (5-11 y/o) and Nurse 2 noticed the syringe that Nurse 1 used to dilute was a 5 cc syringe not a 3 cc syringe. Therefore, the vaccine was diluted with 1.6 mL NS not 1.3 mL. One vial had previously been diluted with the same syringe in the morning session and 10 vaccines were given. Parents of the children who received the vaccine in AM session will be called and notified. Provider, Supervisor and Nurse Manager were notified. Pfizer and CDC COVID Call Centers were called/consulted; both gave the CDC resources/instructions (COVID-19 Vaccine-Administration Errors and Deviations) that states, for this diluent error/deviations ?do not repeat the 1st dose? and they recommended that children receive their second dose as scheduled. Second vial was wasted with 10 doses.

All_symptoms: Abdominal pain Gait disturbance Sleep disorder Ultrasound scan normal
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient awoke several times in the night with abdominal pain.  We treated with Pepto Bismol (antacid) and saw no relief.  In the morning the pain continued and worsened, becoming overwhelmingly severe.  It was painful to walk.  She was carried to the pediatrician's office at 10:15AM.  The pediatrician observed that patient was tender on palpation and advised that we take her immediately to Hospital's outpatient radiology for a sonogram to determine whether she had appendicitis. She ate a light lunch and was fine thereafter.

All_symptoms: Anxiety Dizziness Fall Fear of injection Head injury
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received dose 1 of the pediatric Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot FK5127) at approximately 1710. At 1713, the patient lost consciousness, slumped forward and fell on the ground, hitting her head. PHN and RN responded, assisting the patient supine. The patient was alert and oriented to person, place, and event. At 1715, vital signs: blood pressure 154/88, pulse 124, O2 98%, respirations 20. Patient reported she had felt lightheaded and had a headache before she fell. The patient's father reported that she had no medical conditions, took no medications, and had no allergies. The patient reported she ate prior to arrival. The father reported the patient had no prior history of syncope. RN provided ice pack for head, PHN noted no visible deformity, blood, or skin tear. PHN assessed neurologic function: pupils even and reactive to light accommodation, hand grip strength equal and strong bilaterally, foot strength equal and strong bilaterally. PHN offered to call EMS but patient's father declined. PHN offered Benadryl but patient's father declined. PHN educated on remaining for 30min monitoring from time of syncope, to follow up with provider, and when to call 911 for allergic reaction or concussion symptoms. At 1725, vital signs: blood pressure 146/82, pulse 104, O2 99%, respirations 16. Patient reported all symptoms had resolved but she felt anxious and her extremities are were Patient reported fear of needles. At 1730, patient sat up slowly, continuing to report no symptoms besides anxiety and cold extremities. At 1735, vital signs: blood pressure 142/82, pulse 96, O2 97%, respirations 16. Patient stood up, monitored closely by PHN and RN, and continued to report no symptoms besides anxiety. Patient was tearful. PHN completed concussion protocol and handed to father of patient after explaining. At 1744, vital signs: blood pressure 142/82, O2 100%, pulse 87, respirations 18. Patient reported she still felt anxious after the syncope. At 1745, patient left walking with steady gait, accompanied by father who would drive her home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient experienced a vasovagal reaction to the vaccine. 911 was called to further assess as patient displayed seizure like behavior as well. He lost consciousness momentarily. When he came to, he still was not able to respond well to our questions . His pulse was steady and his breathing was not labored. He threw up 3 times. His complexion was very pale. While EMS providers evaluated him, he continued to respond better to questions, regained his color, and was ultimately able to leave the clinic with his family. EMS determined that he experienced a vasovagal reaction and all his assessments came back within normal limits.
LAB_DATA: 911 was called. Blood pressure was taken (80/30).  EMS performed further assessments.

Pt. received two vaccinations around 3:10pm. He was fine immediately following the injections. He stood up to wait for his father to be vaccinated. After the father's first injection, patient fell back against the plastic cart of supplies and started to lose consciousness. I immediately grabbed him and helped him to the floor. His mother assisted me. I stuck my head out of the consultation room to yell for my team lead. By the time I turned back around, patient was sitting in a chair and fully aware and conscious. I grabbed a fan and started blowing cool air on him while my team lead grabbed some cool cloths. Those were placed at the back of his neck and on his forehead. He was very pale but stayed conscious. I gave him some orange juice and bottled water. After about 15 minutes, his color had returned and he left the room with the assistance of his father. He had reported never having passed out or fainting after a vaccine and he has no known drug allergies.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Child was being held by mother, when I injected the child she jerked away quickly, causing the syringe to pop out and about half of the vaccine liquid to squirt out.  RPH called Pfizer and was referred by them to contact the CDC  to inquire what steps we need to take to ensure child gets her proper dosage. CDC  quoted the  Covid 19 administration errors and deviations guidelines ( dated 11-08-2021) which state to repeat the dose immediately and that a half-dose may be given.  RPH contacted the father who was concerned with the patient receiving too high a dose of vaccine.  Patient's father requested that a third of the pediatric dose be administered instead the full or half-dose.  RPh complied with the parent's request and showed the vaccine dose to the mother when the patient returned to the store on the same day.  Patient received a second injection of 0.05ml which is 1/4 of the dose and the mother was satisfied and agreed with the dosing of the second injection.

All_symptoms: Crying Eye pain Fall Headache Muscle twitching
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client is a 9 yr old female here with her mother for her first covid vaccine. She was very nervous at the time of her vaccine administration at 1645. She was given crackers to eat. At 1648, a loud thud was heard from outside her exam room. PNP entered the room and saw patient face down on the floor. Family member picked her up and laid her on the exam table. She was noted to be pale and crying loudly. HR in the 80s. She was monitored for several minutes attempting to get her to slow her breathing. As she stopped crying, she complained of headache all over and felt like her ""stomach was bleeding."" As she calmed down more, she also complained of right eye pain, left hip pain. She stated her abdomen did not feel strange any longer. She began twitching of her arms and legs intermittently. SHe was offered water, which she was able to drink some of. She did not like the ginger ale so would not drink that. Her Vitals remained stable with HR 89, BP 100/70, O2 SAT 98 on room air. She was rechecked frequently without significant change in her mental status or exam. She was answering questions appropriately.
LAB_DATA: I have discussed the findings and the course of the event with mother. I have discussed that she can likely take her home and feed her and monitor over the next few hours to see how she does vs taking her to the ER for IV fluids and evaluation now. Mother elects to take her to the ED  now for further evaluation. I have notified the ER and discussed emergency precautions with mother. I will report to agency. Follow up as directed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1348:  I was informed by RN, that patient was in the procedure room for c/o SOB and was in no distress.   1350:  Pt was lying on gurney in supine position with his knees bent. Pt was in no respiratory distress, was able to speak in full sentences without pausing, skin pink and warm, pt alert and oriented, answering all questions appropriately.  Pt's mother at bedside.  Vitals taken: BP 103/71 HR 78 SpO2 99% RA.   1358:  Per pt pain onset shortly after he received the vaccine (at 1321) and he sat down on the chair.  No rash noted, no c/o pruritis, no facial swelling, no angioedema noted, nausea and/or vomiting.  No reports of constipation or diarrhea.  Pt reports he ate prior to coming in to get vaccinated.  Pt continues to c/o left sided abdominal pain, constant, improves with his knees bent towards his abdomen and with pressure to LUQ below ribs.  Worse with movement and when he extends his legs. Mid right quad tender to palpation.  Pt did reports having an episode this type of pain before at home, which also started after sitting down in a recliner.  Pain self resolved.  Pt's mother was unaware of incident.   1402:  I have paged incident to provider, Dr., and given report.  Dr.will come in and further evaluate patient.   1405:  I walked in to procedure room and patient was taking sip of water from bottle.  Pt reported pain was gone and got up from gurney without any difficulty, denied pain or any other symptoms.  Pt was moving freely without assistance or guarding.  Pt was in no distress and had no complaints.   1408:  Called Dr. and informed him of change in patient's condition.  Pt will be discharged from clinic. 1410:  Pt instructed to inform his parents shall he develop any symptoms.  Pt's mother was also instructed to monitor for any sxs of severe allergic reaction such as swelling of the tongue, throat, face, difficulty breathing, SOB, generalized rash, abdominal pain, vomiting, dizziness and / or palpitations. In which case pt should get immediate medical attention.  Pt's mother verbalized understanding and pt left in stable condition without any complaints of any symptoms.  Pt stopped to take a picture with the superhero display before leaving.  No signs of distress noted.           My NoteAddendum 2:18 PM  Addend        Patient is a 9 year old male who has completed a 49-minute observation period with the following signs and symptoms of an adverse reaction: other - abdominal pain. Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine #1 in series administered.  o Action(s) taken: Other - Vital Signs o Allergy to COVID-19 vaccine documented in Allergies activity: Yes o Patient advised to discuss second dose considerations with a clinician   RN     RN   1321-Patient received Pfizer tri-sucrose 0.2 dose. 1338-Discharge time. Towards the end of observation, pt began to complain to mom of left side upper quaderant abdominal pain.  1342- Pt was moved to procedure room for comfort. Pt denied difficulty in breathing, itching, nausea. Assessment: Pt presented, skin warm /dry, no rash or flushing.  respirations 14/min not labored, pt rated pain as 3/10 reclined with knees up, exacerbated by independent movement 10/10. RN was brought in to consult. Vitals were done, BP, pulse O2 and heart rate all within normal limits. Attempt was made to palpate abdomen but pt was guarding and recoiled saying ""it tickles"". Overall pt presented relaxed and conversational, no signs of distress with the exception of reported pain. Last oral intake was approximately 30 minutes prior to arrival. Banana, small amount of granola and a partial bottle of water. Last BM within last 24>36 hours. Pt asked for water and took a small sip. Pt related a similar occurrence of a few days ago, which self resolved. Upon hearing the Dr was on his way, pt quickly got up from the bed and said ""Mom, guess what, purified water neutralizes the vaccine!"" Pt then stated ""I'm all better now, let's go home!"" Mom agreed to forego seeing the Dr. Pt departed 1410. Both pt and guardian were educated as to when to call HCP and when to call 911.  Pt was able to ambulate unassisted from the clinic.    1348:  I was informed by RN, that patient was in the procedure room for c/o SOB and was in no distress.   1350:  Pt was lying on gurney in supine position with his knees bent. Pt continues to c/o left sided abdominal pain, constant, improves with his knees bent towards his abdomen and with pressure to LUQ below ribs.  Worse with movement and when he extends his legs. Mid right quad tender to palpation.  Pt did reports having an episode this type of pain before at home, which also started after sitting down in a recliner.  Pain self resolved.  Pt's mother was unaware of incident.   1402:  I have paged incident to provider, Dr., and given report.  Dr. will come in and further evaluate patient.   1405:  I walked in to procedure room and patient was taking sip of water from bottle.  Pt reported pain was gone and got up from gurney without any difficulty, denied pain or any other symptoms.  Pt was moving freely without assistance or guarding.  Pt was in no distress and had no complaints.   1408:  Called Dr. and informed him of change in patient's condition.  Pt will be discharged from clinic. 1410:  Pt instructed to inform his parents shall he develop any symptoms.  Pt's mother was also instructed to monitor for any sxs of severe allergic reaction such as swelling of the tongue, throat, face, difficulty breathing, SOB, generalized rash, abdominal pain, vomiting, dizziness and / or palpitations. In which case pt should get immediate medical attention.  Pt's mother verbalized understanding and pt left in stable condition without any complaints of any symptoms.  Pt stopped to take a picture with the superhero display before leaving.  No signs of distress noted. I wanted to report an incident that happened today at a pharmacy when my daughter was receiving the COVID vaccine.   I brought my 7 year old to the local pharmacy today at 1 pm. The nurse who administered the vaccine wasn't wearing a mask or gloves. She put on one glove when she actually injected my daughter, but wasn't wearing any when handling the vial or the syringe.   When she found out my daughter's age, she unnecessarily commented, ""oh she's so young."" After my daughter received the vaccine, and we were waiting, I overheard the pharmacist and nurse disagreeing about the amount of vaccine that had been given to my daughter, and the other children that day. The pharmacist felt the nurse hadn't given enough in the syringe, neither was going to tell me, but luckily I overheard them and confronted them.  The pharmacist felt the nurse had used too much saline (1.85 ml) to dilute the vaccine, and as a result the nurse should have given a larger amount. The nurse disagreed, and they told me they were waiting for a ""higher up"" at the pharmacy to weigh in.  The nurse said many times that I should not worry about the amount, and just to watch my daughter for side effects.  I now feel that she purposely administered a lower dose. I'm not sure if my daughter received a correct dose, and am quite frustrated that this has happened.   I want to report this so that someone can help me determine if she received a correct dose, and what our next steps should be. And also, to have someone look into the nurse and the incident, so that this doesn't happen to any other children and families.   I have reported this to the pharmacy, and am awaiting a response from the District Manager. I'm not sure if you can help, or if this is relevant to you, but someone provided your contact info and suggested I share as you are researching a similar incident at another pharmacy.   I'm happy to answer any questions you might have. Thank you!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shortly after getting vaccinated, patient sat down for a 15 min wait period. She immediately started having trouble breathing and complained of stomach pain and a desire to vomit. I took her to the bathroom, she started getting hot, complained that it was getting harder to breathe, and seemed a little confused/didn't register what I was saying to keep her calm and wanting her to get out of the bathroom so we could speak with the pharmacist for help. I got her out, and the pharmacist helped me to refill her albuterol prescription (she needs it so rarely, when she has a cold, we didn't have it with us + she's never had an adverse reaction to a vaccine). That helped immediately. She drank some water. She then went back to the bathroom and had diarrhea. After that, we hung out for another 30+ minutes. Her breathing stabilized, she didn't need more albuterol, and she said she felt much better.  We're still less than 12 hrs. out from the vaccine as I write, so we are monitoring for any symptoms, and encouraging her to rest and drink fluids. I've also contacted her dr. to give a heads up.

It was reported to this writer, RN that 11 year-old male minor patient accompanied by his mother was vaccinated on 11/08/2021 for Pfizer COVID-19 vaccination by LPN at 03:58pm. Patient and his mother reported patient initially tolerated vaccination well and was stable when escorted to clinical site. Around 4:04pm when patient was sitting in post-vaccination observation area with mother, his mother noticed that he was not feeling well while both were sitting in chairs. Mother reports she noticed that her son became disoriented and per her report ?began bobbing his head back and forth with his eyes closed?. It was reported to this writer that RN who was assisting in supervising patients in the post-vaccination observation area responded while patient was seated and assessed that he was pale and drowsy. RN reported she gave the patient apple juice. Shortly after the patient stated that he felt better and was escorted by RN with mother present to private medical cot area to lie down. This writer immediately responded to the medical incident to support clinical staff and observed the patient was stable but still pale. RN took serial vitals for patient that were within defined limits. Patient was given more apple juice and said he felt better at 04:09pm and told his mother with clinical staff present that he only had a small snack after school and 1 hour before his mother had picked him up from school. Patient also stated that when clinical staff in post-observation area began talking again about possible vaccine side effects with mother that patient said he got scared and anxious. After 10 minutes of resting on the medical cot with mother and RN staff present and another round of stable vital signs noted by RNs, patient stated he felt good and slowly stood up at the side of the cot. Patient denied any dizziness or feelings of weakness. Patient skin color returned with defined limits, no paleness noted. Patient ambulated in the care of his mother who was driving them both home at that time out of the clinic without any issues or adventitious findings at 04:21pm.
LAB_DATA: unknown, no tests performed by clinical staff present at vaccination site the day of incident 11/08/2021.

All_symptoms: Fall Loss of consciousness Pallor Skin warm
SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot#FK1527) in the L deltoid and the Fluarix Quadrivalent Influenza Vaccine (Lot#3NA4M) in the R deltoid at approximately 1050 from vaccinator RN. After the client received both vaccines, he stood up to wait next to his mother who was receiving her COVID vaccine from the same vaccinator. Due to a limited supply of chairs at the mobile event there was not an available chair to allow the client to sit down while waiting with his mother. At approximately 1055, as the client was standing next to his mother, he began to slouch over the vaccination table and vaccinator RN's assisted client to the ground. Client lost consciousness for approximately 2 seconds. RN assessed non obstructed airway, no respiratory distress, and raised the client's legs while he was laying on the floor. RN assessed client who presented with mild pallor of the face, no diaphoresis, and pupils equal and reactive. RN took client vitals at 1103 with BP 100/60 in the L arm laying down, 70 HR, and 16 RR. Lead RN assessed client at 1103 presented A&O x4 and talking in full sentences,  grip strong and equal, cap refill < 3 seconds, and skin pink and warm to touch.  Client's mother reported that the client ate breakfast at 0830 and had a muffin. Client denied dizziness, SOB, headache, numbness, or tingling. Client was assisted to zero-gravity chair and Lead RN advised that the client be observed for 30 minutes. Client's father reported that he has a history of fainting but reported that the client has never fainted in the past. Lead RN provided client with water, juice, and graham crackers. Client took sips of the water and juice and ate his snacks. Client reported to Lead RN that he was ""feeling good now"" and denied any dizziness, SOB, headache, numbness, or tingling. RN reviewed when to f/u with PCP. At 1140 the client left the vaccine site with his parents. Client walked out of the vaccine site with a steady and symmetrical gait.

All_symptoms: Hyperhidrosis Pallor Somnolence Syncope Unresponsive to stimuli
SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received dose 1 of the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot FK5127) at 1212. At 1220, the patient's body went limp and his head slumped forwards while sitting in his father's arms. The patient's father called for help. Patient's mother reported the patient was not responding to verbal stimuli. PHN and PHN approached to assess patient. Patient appeared pale and diaphoretic. Patient started responding to verbal stimuli asking ""what's going on?"" PHN and father assisted patient to the ground. Vital signs: blood pressure 90/58, O2 99%, pulse 84, respirations 24. At 1225, patient reported he saw black and felt sleepy but currently symptoms improved. Patient's mother reported patient had allergies to ibuprofen and bandage adhesive, no medical conditions, and takes no medication. PHN offered Benadryl but patient's mother declined. PHN educated on remaining for 30min monitoring from time symptoms started, to follow up with provider, and ER precautions. Patient's mother reported that patient had no prior history of syncope. PHN offered patient water and applesauce but patient declined. At 1228, patient reported symptoms had resolved. Vital signs: blood pressure 94/62, O2 99%, pulse 78, respirations 20. At 1245, patient sat up, continued reporting no symptoms. Vital signs: blood pressure 92/60, O2 99%, pulse 80, respirations 18. At 1248, patient stood up, continued reporting no symptoms. Patient left walking with steady gait at 1250 accompanied by parents and sibling.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the vaccine and then walked approximately 50 feet to the post-vaccination observation area, where we were directed to a seating area. She sat down, told me (her mother) that she was tired and a little dizzy, and then her head rolled to the right side and her body went slack?she passed out. I immediately started saying her name and tapping her shoulder and face to wake her up, while also signaling to the clinic staff that she needed help. She twitched a few times while passed out but didn?t wake up for about 15-20 seconds. Then, she abruptly opened her eyes and was alert though really tired. She said she was okay, but she was sweaty, pale and slow to move. She was able to transfer herself to a wheelchair and was taken to a separate observation area where she was allowed to lay down while a nurse checked her vitals. She was given some water followed by some grape juice. We waited another 15 minutes in this area until patient was feeling well enough to get up and move around. She was cleared to leave and we left around 1:35 p.m. She was tired for the rest of the day and had a sore arm near the injection site, but had no additional symptoms after this incident.
